Loading Packages

We will start by loading some useful packages. Using the library function, we can load these packages if they have previously been installed in your R. If they have not been previously installed, replace the library function with install.packages function and place the package name in quotation marks. That will install the package. Next, run the library function again and it will load the package. You only need to install a package once.

library(ggplot2) # Necessary for `ggplot` function.
library(dplyr) # Necessary for `%>%` and `mutate` function.
library(kableExtra) # Necessary for `kbl` function.
library(tidyr) # Necessary for `pivot_longer` function.
library(reshape2) # Necessary for `melt` function
library(Rmisc) # Necessary for the 'summarySE' function. 
library(png) # Necessary for `png` function.
library(report) # Necessary for `report` function.
library(readxl) # Necessary for `read_excel` function.
library(ggpubr) # Necessary for `ggarrange` function.
library(multcomp) # Necessary for 'glht' function. 
library(effects) # Necessary for 'allEffects' function.

Dataframe Setup

Loading Dataframes

We will set the working directory using the setwd function. If you are looking to run this code in your computer, be sure to change the path to your data! Normally we can load data frames using the read.csv function. Or, we can use the read_excel function from the readxl package and specify the sheet number!

setwd("~/Desktop/R") # Set the working directory
EFB_Biomass <- read_excel("Data/EFB_Data.xlsx", sheet = 1)
EFB_PHB <- read_excel("Data/EFB_Data.xlsx", sheet = 2)
EFB_Sugars <- read_excel("Data/EFB_Data.xlsx", sheet = 3)
FruitBunch <- read_excel("Data/EFB_Data.xlsx", sheet = 4)

Variable Formatting

We can convert multiple variables into numerical or factorial class by combining as.numeric or as.factor with the mutate function from the dplyr package as well as the across function on a concatenated list of our variables.

EFB_Biomass <- EFB_Biomass %>%
  dplyr::mutate(across(c("Sugar", "Replicate"), as.factor))
EFB_PHB <- EFB_PHB %>%
  dplyr::mutate(across(c("Sugar", "Replicate"), as.factor))
EFB_Sugars <- EFB_Sugars %>%
  dplyr::mutate(across(c("Sugar", "Replicate"), as.factor))
FruitBunch <- FruitBunch %>%
  dplyr::mutate(across(c("Variable"), as.factor))

Biomass_tgc <- summarySE(EFB_Biomass, measurevar="Biomass_Concentration", groupvars=c("Time", "Sugar"), na.rm = TRUE)
PHB_tgc <- summarySE(EFB_PHB, measurevar="PHB_Concentration", groupvars=c("Time", "Sugar"), na.rm = TRUE)

Super! Now, we are going to want to work with the assay individually, so we will have to do some reconfiguring. Using the subset and droplevels functions, we will create new dataframes that separate the Biomass_tgc, PHB_tgc, and Sugars_tgc by sugar.

BiomassGlucose <- droplevels(subset(Biomass_tgc, Biomass_tgc$Sugar == "Glucose"))
BiomassArabinose <- droplevels(subset(Biomass_tgc, Biomass_tgc$Sugar == "Arabinose"))
BiomassXylose <- droplevels(subset(Biomass_tgc, Biomass_tgc$Sugar == "Xylose"))

PHBGlucose <- droplevels(subset(PHB_tgc, PHB_tgc$Sugar == "Glucose"))
PHBArabinose <- droplevels(subset(PHB_tgc, PHB_tgc$Sugar == "Arabinose"))
PHBXylose <- droplevels(subset(PHB_tgc, PHB_tgc$Sugar == "Xylose"))

SugarsGlucose <- droplevels(subset(Sugars_tgc, Sugars_tgc$Sugar == "Glucose"))
SugarsArabinose <- droplevels(subset(Sugars_tgc, Sugars_tgc$Sugar == "Arabinose"))
SugarsXylose <- droplevels(subset(Sugars_tgc, Sugars_tgc$Sugar == "Xylose"))

Next we work with individual sugars.

Great. Now, we do have some extra columns here, so letâs use some bracket notation to specify that we only want the first, second, fourth, and sixth column, which correspond to the variables Time, Sugar, Concentrations, and se, which is standard error, our dispersion statistic of interest.

BiomassArabinose <- BiomassArabinose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
PHBArabinose <- PHBArabinose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
SugarsArabinose <- SugarsArabinose[,c(1,2,4,6)]

BiomassArabinose$Variable <- "Biomass"
PHBArabinose$Variable <- "PHB"
SugarsArabinose$Sugars <- "Arabinose"

BiomassGlucose <- BiomassGlucose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
PHBGlucose <- PHBGlucose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
SugarsGlucose <- SugarsGlucose[,c(1,2,4,6)]

BiomassGlucose$Variable <- "Biomass"
PHBGlucose$Variable <- "PHB"
SugarsGlucose$Sugars <- "Glucose"

BiomassXylose <- BiomassXylose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
PHBXylose <- PHBXylose[,c(1,2,4,6)]
SugarsXylose <- SugarsXylose[,c(1,2,4,6)]

BiomassXylose$Variable <- "Biomass"
PHBXylose$Variable <- "PHB"
SugarsXylose$Sugars <- "Xylose"

Next, we can use colnames to specify some names for these new dataframes. We will conserve the Variable column, as this one will tell us in the future, whether this is biomass, PHB, or sugar concentration. Finally, we will use rbind to bind together these dataframes together by rows, given their shared columns.

colnames(BiomassArabinose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(PHBArabinose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(SugarsArabinose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")

colnames(BiomassGlucose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(PHBGlucose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(SugarsGlucose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")

colnames(BiomassXylose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(PHBXylose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")
colnames(SugarsXylose) <- c("Time", "Sugar", "Concentration", "se", "Variable")

Arabinose <- rbind(BiomassArabinose, PHBArabinose, SugarsArabinose)
Xylose <- rbind(BiomassXylose, PHBXylose, SugarsXylose)
Glucose <- rbind(BiomassGlucose,PHBGlucose,SugarsGlucose)

Almost ready to graph. First, we will need to reclassify the Variable column to be a factor, using the as.factor function.

Arabinose$Variable <- as.factor(Arabinose$Variable)
Glucose$Variable <- as.factor(Glucose$Variable)
Xylose$Variable <- as.factor(Xylose$Variable)

Statistics

Beautiful. Now we are ready to start calculating some key statistics. To do so, first we need to isolate some key numbers, such as the initial and final concentrations of substrate, PHB, and biomass. To do this, we will once again use the subset and droplevels functions to isolate rows where Time is equal to zero or 72.

Arabinose0 <- droplevels(subset(Arabinose, Arabinose$Time == "0"))
Arabinose72 <- droplevels(subset(Arabinose, Arabinose$Time == "72"))

Glucose0 <- droplevels(subset(Glucose, Glucose$Time == "0"))
Glucose72 <- droplevels(subset(Glucose, Glucose$Time == "72"))

Xylose0 <- droplevels(subset(Xylose, Xylose$Time == "0"))
Xylose72 <- droplevels(subset(Xylose, Xylose$Time == "72"))

Now, we can easily isolate numbers we need.

Isolating Statistics

Arabinose

AraInitialSub <- Arabinose0[3,3]
AraFinalSub <- Arabinose72[3,3]

AraInitialBiomass <- Arabinose0[1,3]
AraFinalBiomass <- Arabinose72[1,3]

AraInitialPHB <- Arabinose0[2,3]
AraFinalPHB <- Arabinose72[2,3]

AraBioDiff <- AraFinalBiomass - AraInitialBiomass
AraPHBDiff <- AraFinalPHB - AraInitialPHB
AraConsumption <- AraInitialSub - AraFinalSub

AraYield <- (AraFinalBiomass - AraInitialBiomass) / (AraInitialSub - AraFinalSub)
AraPHBYield <- (AraFinalPHB - AraInitialPHB) / (AraInitialSub - AraFinalSub)
AraPHBRate <- AraPHBDiff/72
AraPercentPHB <- AraFinalPHB/AraFinalBiomass*100

EFB

For the EFB, first we need to create a new column Variable2 in the FruitBunch dataframe. The values of Variable2 are based on the values in the existing Variable column. Specifically, if the value in the Variable column is âGlucoseâ or âXyloseâ, the corresponding value in the Variable2 column is set to âSugarâ. For all other values in the Variable column, Variable2 is set to the same value as Variable. This will allow us to calculate statistics for the substrate not separated by sugar.

FruitBunch <- FruitBunch %>%
  mutate(Variable2 = ifelse(Variable == "Glucose" | Variable == "Xylose", "Sugar", as.character(Variable)))

Now we use the summarySE function to calculate descriptive statistics using the Time and Variable2 columns.

FruitBunch2_tgc <- summarySE(FruitBunch, measurevar="Value", groupvars=c("Time", "Variable2"), na.rm = TRUE)

We can now isolate Time = 0 or 72.

FruitBunch3_tgc <- FruitBunch2_tgc %>%
  filter(Time == 0 | Time == 72)

Now we can isolate the statistics that we are interested in.

EFBInitialBiomass <- FruitBunch3_tgc[1,4]
EFBFinalBiomass <- FruitBunch3_tgc[5,4]

EFBInitialPHB <- FruitBunch3_tgc[2,4]
EFBFinalPHB <- FruitBunch3_tgc[6,4]

EFBInitialSub <- FruitBunch3_tgc[3,4]
EFBFinalSub <- FruitBunch3_tgc[7,4]

EFBBioDiff <- EFBFinalBiomass - EFBInitialBiomass
EFBConsumption <- EFBInitialSub - EFBFinalSub
EFBPHBDiff <- EFBFinalPHB - EFBInitialPHB

EFBYield <- (EFBFinalBiomass - EFBInitialBiomass) / (EFBInitialSub - EFBFinalSub)
EFBPHBYield <- (EFBFinalPHB - EFBInitialPHB) / (EFBInitialSub - EFBFinalSub)
EFBPHBRate <- EFBPHBDiff/72
EFBPercentPHB <- EFBFinalPHB/EFBFinalBiomass*100

EFB_Biomass2 <- EFB_Biomass[EFB_Biomass$Time %in% c(0, 72), ]

time_0 <- EFB_Biomass2 %>% filter(Time == 0)
